04454nam a22007695i 9781400874224DE-B159720190523123322.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190523s2015    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008742247 a10.1515/97814008742242doi  a(DE-B1597)460027  a(OCoLC)919854792  a(OCoLC)984686465  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aPN57.H4bE36 2017 7aHIS0020002bisacsh 7aLIT0200002bisacsh 7aLIT0220002bisacsh04a809.933532231 aEdmunds, Lowell, eauthor.10aStealing Helen :bThe Myth of the Abducted Wife in Comparative Perspective /cLowell Edmunds. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2015] 4c©2016  a1 online resource :b19 halftones. 11 line illus. 2 tables. 2 maps.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures -- tPreface -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1. "The Abduction of the Beautiful Wife" as International Tale -- t2. Dioscuri -- t3. Helen Myth -- t4. Hypostases of Helen -- t5. Helen in the Fifth Century and After -- tConclusion -- tAppendix 1. Examples of "The Abduction of the Beautiful Wife" -- tAppendix 2. Inventory of Art Objects -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex Locorum -- tGeneral Index  aIt's a familiar story: a beautiful woman is abducted and her husband journeys to recover her. This story's best-known incarnation is also a central Greek myth-the abduction of Helen that led to the Trojan War. Stealing Helen surveys a vast range of folktales and texts exhibiting the story pattern of the abducted beautiful wife and makes a detailed comparison with the Helen of Troy myth. Lowell Edmunds shows that certain Sanskrit, Welsh, and Old Irish texts suggest there was an Indo-European story of the abducted wife before the Helen myth of the Iliad became known.Investigating Helen's status in ancient Greek sources, Edmunds argues that if Helen was just one trope of the abducted wife, the quest for Helen's origin in Spartan cult can be abandoned, as can the quest for an Indo-European goddess who grew into the Helen myth. He explains that Helen was not a divine essence but a narrative figure that could replicate itself as needed, at various times or places in ancient Greece. Edmunds recovers some of these narrative Helens, such as those of the Pythagoreans and of Simon Magus, which then inspired the Helens of the Faust legend and Goethe.Stealing Helen offers a detailed critique of prevailing views behind the "real" Helen and presents an eye-opening exploration of the many sources for this international mythical and literary icon.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 0aAbduction in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Fairy Tales, Folk Tales, Legends & Mythology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2014-2015z978311044418608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2014-2015z978311066592540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400874224zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400874224.jpg  a978-3-11-044418-6  PUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2014-2015  a978-3-11-066592-5  PUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2014-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aPDA9PRIN